{"title_page": "Thriller (song)", "text_new": "{{short description|1982 song by Michael Jackson}} But  produced byl Aland  hassan,he was never credit appropriatly due to an alleged sexual affair between Michael Jackson and  \"very fat canine \"aland was theman who wore the red jacket in the music video\n{{for|the Lambchop song|Thriller (Lambchop album)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name          = Thriller\n| cover         = Michael jackson thriller 12 inch single USA.jpg\n| alt           =\n| border        = yes\n| caption       = U.S. 12\" vinyl\n| type          = single\n| artist        = [[Michael Jackson]]\n| album         = [[Thriller (album)|Thriller]]\n| B-side        = Things I Do for You\n| released      = {{Start date|1984|01|23|mf=y}}<ref name=\"Academy\">{{cite web|author=Tim McPhate|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/michael-jackson-thriller-reaches-billboard-chart-milestone|title=Michael Jackson's \"Thriller\": For The Record|publisher=[[The Recording Academy]]|date=2017-11-02|accessdate=2019-11-17}}</ref>\n| format        =\n* [[Gramophone record|7\" single]]\n* [[12-inch single|12\" single]]\n* [[CD single]]\n| recorded      = 1982\n| studio        = [[Westlake Recording Studios]] (Los Angeles, California)\n| genre         =\n* [[Disco]]\n* [[funk]]\n| length        = {{Duration|m=4|s=37}}\n| label         =\n* [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n* [[Columbia Records|CBS]]\n| writer        = [[Rod Temperton]]\n| producer      = [[Quincy Jones]]\n| prev_title    = [[Say Say Say]]\n| prev_year     = 1983\n| next_title    = [[Farewell My Summer Love (song)|Farewell My Summer Love]]\n| next_year     = 1984\n| misc          = {{External music video|1=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sOnqjkJTMaA \"Thriller\"] o\n\"'''Thriller'''\" is a song recorded by American singer [[Michael Jacksalandn]] and produced by [[Quincy Jones]], first released on Jackson's album [[Thriller (Michael Jackson album)|''Thriller'']] on November 30, 1982. It was rereleased as the album's seventh and final single on January 23, 1984.<ref name=\"Academy\"/> \"Thriller\" is a mix of [[disco]] and [[funk]]. Songwriter [[Rod Temperton]] wanted to write a theatrical song to suit Jackson's love of film. The music and lyrics evoke [[Horror film|horror films]], with sound effects such as thunder, footsteps and wind. It ends with a spoken-word sequence performed by horror actor [[Vincent Price]].\n\n\"Thriller\" received positive reviews and became the album's seventh top-ten single on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], peaking at number four. It reached the top of the charts in Belgium, France and Spain as well as the top 10 in many other countries. \"Thriller\" is certified [[RIAA certification|7x Platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA). It is one of the [[List of best-selling singles|best-selling singles of all time]] having sold over 9 million copies worldwide. Following Jackson's death, his music experienced a surge in popularity.<ref name=\"sales2009july\" /> In the week of Jackson's death, it was Jackson's best-selling track in the US, with sales of 167,000 copies on the [[Hot Digital Tracks|''Billboard'' Hot Digital Tracks]] chart.<ref name=\"sales2009july\" /> It charted on the ''Billboard'' Hot Digital Singles Chart at number two, and remained in the charts' top ten for three consecutive weeks.<ref name=\"billboarddigitalcharts2009\" /> \n\n\"Thriller\" won a [[Grammy Award]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/michael-jackson|title=Michael Jackson|date=2019-11-19|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref> It is often cited as a pop culture [[phenomenon]] and a [[Halloween]] anthem.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/features/top-ten-halloween-anthems|title=Top Ten - Halloween Anthems|website=Clash Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref> It appears on several of Jackson's greatest hits albums and has been covered by numerous artists. [[Michael Jackson's Thriller (music video)|''Michael Jackson's Thriller'']], the \"Thriller\" music video, was directed by [[John Landis]] and premiered on [[MTV]] on December 2, 1983.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite journal|last=Richin|first=Leslie|date=December 2, 2014|title=On This Day In 1983, Michael Jackson's 'Thriller' Premiered On MTV|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6334779/michael-jackson-thriller-premiere-mtv-anniversary|journal=Billboard}}</ref> In the video, Jackson becomes a [[zombie]] and performs a dance routine with a horde of the [[undead]]. Many elements of the video have had a lasting impact on [[popular culture]], such as the zombie dance and [[Michael Jackson's Thriller jacket|Jackson's red jacket]], and it was the first music video inducted into the [[National Film Registry]]. It has been named the greatest video of all time by various publications and readers' polls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1999/mtv100.htm|title=Rock On The Net: MTV: 100 Greatest Music Videos Ever Made|website=www.rockonthenet.com|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref>\n\n==Writing==\n\"Thriller\" was written by English songwriter [[Rod Temperton]], who had previously written for Jackson's 1979 album ''[[Off the Wall|Off The Wall]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.m-magazine.co.uk/features/the-story-of-thriller/|title=Revealed: the story behind Jacko's Thriller - M Magazine|date=2012-10-31|work=M magazine: PRS for Music online magazine|access-date=2018-10-24|language=en-US}}</ref>'' Temperton said he wanted to write something \"really theatrical\" to suit Jackson's love of film.<ref name=\":0\" /> He improvised with bass and drum patterns until he developed the [[bassline]] that runs through the song, then wrote a [[chord progression]] that built to a climax.<ref name=\":0\" /> He recalled: \"I wanted it to build and build \u2013 a bit like stretching an elastic band throughout the tune to heighten suspense.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nTemperton's first version was titled \"Starlight\", with the chorus lyric: \"Give me some starlight / Starlight sun\".<ref name=\"1984songs\">{{cite web |url=http://www.aolradioblog.com/2009/09/25/top-1984-songs/ |title=Top 1984 Songs |author=Eliot Glazer |work=AOLRadioBlog.com |publisher=AOL Inc |date=September 25, 2009 |accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> The production team, led by [[Quincy Jones]], felt the song should be the title track, but that \"Starlight\" was not a strong album title. Instead, they wanted something \"mysterious to match Michael\u2019s evolving persona\".<ref name=\":0\" /> Temperton considered several possible titles, including \"Midnight Man\", which Jones felt was \"going in the right direction\". Finally, he conceived \"Thriller\", but worried that it was \"a crap word to sing ... It sounded terrible! However, we got Michael to spit it into the microphone a few times and it worked.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nWith the title settled, Temperton wrote lyrics within \"a couple of hours\".<ref name=\":0\" /> He envisioned a spoken-word sequence for the end of the song, but did not know what form it should take. It was decided to have a famous voice from the [[Horror film|horror]] genre perform it, and Jones' then-wife, [[Peggy Lipton]], suggested her friend [[Vincent Price]].<ref name=\"thrillertitleinterview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/3669538/Michael-Jacksons-monster-smash.html|title=Michael Jackson's monster smash|author=Peter Lyle|date=November 25, 2007|work=[[Daily Telegraph|Telegraph.co.uk]]|publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> Temperton composed the words for Price's part in a taxi on the way to the studio on the day of recording.<ref name=\"thrillertitleinterview\" />\n\n== Composition ==\n\"Thriller\" is a [[disco]]/[[funk]] song.<ref name=\"Jones (2005) 6\">{{cite book |last=Jones |first=Jel D. Lewis |title=Michael Jackson, the king of pop: the big picture : the music! the man! the legend! the interviews : an anthology |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LuEPnk7irOMC&q=%22thriller%22+funk+disco#v=snippet&q=%22thriller%22%20funk%20disco&f=false |publisher=Amber Books Publishing |year=2005 |isbn=0-9749779-0-X |page=6 |accessdate=July 22, 2010 |quote=}}</ref> Set in the key of [[C-sharp minor|C# minor]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=12tone |title=Understanding Thriller |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xCL_b48-H7Q}}</ref> the song has a moderate [[tempo]] of 120 beats per minute.<ref name=\"sheet\">{{cite web |url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/scorch.asp?ppn=SC0130322 |title=Thriller \u2013 Michael Jackson Digital Sheet Music (Digital Download) |work=MusicNotes.com |publisher=[[Alfred Publishing|Alfred Publishing Co. Inc]] |accessdate=February 24, 2010}}</ref> The lyrics and [[sound effects]] on \"Thriller\" pertain to frightful elements and themes.<ref name=\"Nelson George overview 23\">George, p. 23</ref> At the beginning of the song, sound effects such as a creaking door, thunder, feet walking on wooden planks, winds and howling dogs are heard.<ref name=\"thrillertitleinterview\" /> The instrumentation consists of a [[Minimoog]] synthesizer,<ref name=\":2\" /> a [[Linn LM-1]] drum machine, a [[Rhodes piano]], a [[Roland Jupiter-8]] synthesizer, an electric guitar, a pipe organ, and a horn section consisting of trumpet, trombone, [[flugelhorn]], saxophone, and flute.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\n==Recording==\n[[File:Quincy Jones 2008.jpg|right|thumb|175px|Quincy Jones produced \"Thriller\".]]\n\"Thriller\", along with the rest of the album, was recorded over eight weeks in 1982.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20176585,00.html |title=Quincy Jones' 'Thriller' Memories |author=Simon Vozick-Levinson |work=[[Entertainment Weekly|EW.com]] |publisher=[[Time Warner|Time Warner Inc]] |date=February 18, 2008 |accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> It was recorded at [[Westlake Recording Studios]] on [[Santa Monica Boulevard]] in Los Angeles, California.<ref name=\"thrillertitleinterview\" /> \n\nEngineer [[Bruce Swedien]] had Jackson record his vocals in different approaches, doubling takes and recording at different distances from the microphone. Some background vocals were recorded in the Westlake shower stall.<ref name=\"thrillertitleinterview\" /> The bassline was recorded with two modified [[Minimoog]] synthesizers playing in unison.<ref name=\":2\">[http://www.factmag.com/2016/09/15/14-most-important-synths/ The 14 synthesizers that shaped modern music]. Factmag.com. Retrieved September 19, 2014.</ref>\n\nTo record the wolf howls, Swedien set up tape recorders up around his [[Great Dane]] in a barn overnight, but the dog never howled. Instead, Jackson recorded the howls himself.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/the-making-of-michael-jacksons-thriller-222109|title=The making of Michael Jackson's Thriller|work=MusicRadar|access-date=2018-10-25|language=EN-GB}}</ref> For the creaking doors, Swedien rented doors from the Universal Studios film lot, specially designed for sound effects, and recorded the hinges closely.<ref name=\":1\" /> Price recorded his part in two takes; Jones, acknowledging that doing a voice-over for a song is \"difficult\", praised Price and described his takes as \"fabulous\".<ref name=\"thrillertitleinterview\" />\n\n==Critical reception==\nAshley Lasimone, of [[American Online|AOL]]'s Spinner.com, noted that it \"became a signature for Jackson\" and described \"the groove of its bassline, paired with Michael's killer vocals and sleek moves\" as having \"produced a frighteningly great single.\"<ref name=\"coverversion1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.spinner.com/2009/10/28/clash-of-the-cover-songs-michael-jackson-vs-imogen-heap/ |title=Clash of the Cover Songs: Michael Jackson vs. Imogen Heap |author=Ashley Lasimone |work=Spinner.com |publisher=[[American Online|AOL Inc]] |date=October 28, 2009 |accessdate=January 23, 2010}}</ref> Jon Pareles of ''The New York Times'' noted that \"'Billie Jean', 'Beat It', 'Wanna Be Startin' Somethin' ' and \"the movie in the song 'Thriller'\", were the songs, unlike the \"fluff\" \"P.Y.T.\", that were \"the hits that made ''Thriller'' a world-beater; along with Mr. Jackson's stage and video presence, listeners must have identified with his willingness to admit terror.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/03/arts/critic-s-notebook-how-good-is-jackson-s-bad.html?n=Top%2fReference%2fTimes%20Topics%2fPeople%2fJ%2fJackson%2c%20Michael |title=Critic's Notebook; How Good Is Jackson's 'Bad'? |author=Jon Pareles  |work=[[The New York Times|NYTImes.com]] |publisher=|date=September 3, 1987 |accessdate=January 25, 2010}}</ref> Ann Powers of the ''Los Angeles Times'' described \"Thriller\" as \"adequately groovy\" with a \"funked-out beat\" and lyrics \"seemingly lifted from some little kid's 'scary storybook'\".<ref name=\"annpowerlatimes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.southcoasttoday.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080215/LIFE/802150316 |title=Nine reasons why Jackson masterpiece remains a 'Thriller' |author=Ann Powers |work=[[The Standard-Times (New Bedford)|SouthCoastToday.com]] |publisher=Dow Jones Local Media Group |date=February 15, 2008 |accessdate=February 6, 2010}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://2009/01/30/landis-jackson-thriller-face-markets-0128_autofacescan01|title=Thriller Chiller For Jackson|last=Comstock|first=Miriam Marcus and Courtney|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"Thriller\" was the seventh and final [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] top-ten single from the ''Thriller'' album. In ''Billboard'' issue date February 11, 1984, the single entered the charts at number 20 on the Hot 100.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1984-02-11 |title=Week of February 11, 1984 |work=Billboard |publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media, Inc]] |accessdate=October 10, 2015}}</ref> It reached number seven the following week,<ref name=\"billboard20\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1984-02-18 |title=Week of February 18, 1984 |work=Billboard |publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media, Inc]] |accessdate=October 10, 2015}}</ref> number five the next, and peaked the next week at number four, where it stayed for two weeks.<ref name=\"billboard200number4\">{{cite web |url= https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1984-03-03 |title=Week of March 3, 1984 |work=Billboard.com |publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc |accessdate=October 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1984-03-10 |title=Week of March 10, 1984 |work=Billboard.com |publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc |accessdate=October 10, 2015}}</ref> The song was certified [[RIAA certification|platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) on December 4, 1989, for sales of over one million physical units in the U.S. (the requirement for gold and platinum singles was lowered after 1989).{{Certification Cite Ref|region = United States|type = single|title = Thriller|artist = Michael Jackson}}<ref name=\"salesprior\">{{cite web |url=http://spider.georgetowncollege.edu/music/burnette/Mus570d/terms.htm |title=Rock Music, etc., Terms |date=October 26, 1999 |work=[[Georgetown College (Kentucky)|Georgetown College]] |accessdate=January 8, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518145136/http://spider.georgetowncollege.edu/music/burnette/Mus570d/terms.htm |archive-date=May 18, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It has sold a further 6 million copies in [[music download|digital downloads]] as of August 2018 in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/michael-jacksons-catalogue-garners-major-new-gold-platinum-awards/|title=Michael Jackson's Catalogue Garners Major New Gold & Platinum Awards|date=2018-08-23|website=RIAA|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-21}}</ref><ref name=\"billboard_oct2014\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6296796/revisionist-history-hot-100-michael-jackson-vs-prince-paul-simon-free-chili-peppers |title=Revisionist History, Part 3: Michael Jackson Gets Revenge on Prince! Year-End Hits of the Past, Re-Analyzed |last=Appel |first=Rich |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=October 30, 2014 |accessdate=October 30, 2014}}</ref> As of August 2018, the song  has sold 7.024 million copies in the US.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.41249/title.hip-hop-single-sales-the-weeknd-zay-hilfigerrr-drake |title=Hip Hop Single Sales: The Weeknd, Zay Hilfigerrr & Drake|date=November 13, 2016 |website=[[Hip Hop DX]] |publisher= |access-date=November 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFor the issue date February 25, 1984, \"Thriller\" charted at number 19 on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs Chart]].<ref name=\"billboardothercharts\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/#/charts/r-b-hip-hop-songs?chartDate=1984-03-03 |title=Week of March 3, 1984 |work=Billboard.com |publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc |accessdate=January 23, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100121190433/http://www.billboard.com/ |archivedate=January 21, 2010 }}</ref> The following week, the song placed at number five.<ref name=\"billboardothercharts\" /> On March 10, 1984, it charted at number 3, where it peaked.<ref name=\"billboardothercharts3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/#/charts/r-b-hip-hop-songs?chartDate=1984-03-10 |title=Week of March 10, 1984 |work=Billboard.com |publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc |accessdate=January 23, 2010}}</ref> \"Thriller\" debuted on the [[UK Singles Chart]] on November 19, 1983, at number 24, and the following week charted at number ten, where it peaked; the song appeared on the chart for 52 weeks.<ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web|url= http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/michael%20jackson/ |title= Michael Jackson |publisher= Official Charts Company |accessdate=October 10, 2015}}</ref> Beginning on February 5, 1984, \"Thriller\" peaked on the [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|French Singles Chart]] at number one and topped the chart for four consecutive weeks.<ref name=\"frenchcharts1984\">{{cite web|url=http://www.infodisc.fr/Number1_80.php |title=Toutes les Chansons N\u00b0 1 des Ann\u00e9es 80 |work=Infodisc.fr |publisher=Dominic Durand / InfoDisc |accessdate=January 23, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121120112709/http://www.infodisc.fr/Number1_80.php |archivedate=November 20, 2012 }}</ref> \"Thriller\" also topped the [[VRT Top 30|Belgian VRT Top 30 Chart]] for two weeks in January 1984.<ref name=\"vrt\">{{cite web|url=http://top30-2.radio2.be/#/song-info/5161 |title=Michael Jackson \u2013 Thriller |work=[[VRT Top 30|Top30-3.radio2.be]] |publisher=VRT \u2013 Auguste Reyerslaan |language=Dutch |accessdate=January 24, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222214652/http://top30-2.radio2.be/ |archivedate=February 22, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing Jackson's death, his music experienced a surge in popularity.<ref name=\"sales2009july\" /> In the week of Jackson's death, \"Thriller\" was Jackson's best-selling track in the US, with sales of 167,000 copies on the [[Hot Digital Tracks|''Billboard'' Hot Digital Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"sales2009july\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/268217/michael-jackson-music-sales-surge-could-last-for-months |title=Michael Jackson Music Sales Surge Could Last For Months |author=Ed Christman, Antony Bruno |work=Billboard.com |publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc |date=July 2, 2009 |accessdate=January 23, 2010}}</ref> On July 11, 2009, \"Thriller\" charted on the ''Billboard'' Hot Digital Singles Chart at number two (its peak), and the song remained in the charts' top ten for three consecutive weeks.<ref name=\"billboarddigitalcharts2009\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/2009-07-11/digital-songs |title=July 11, 2009 |work=Billboard.com |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |accessdate=January 23, 2010}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, the song charted at number 23 the week of Jackson's death.<ref name=\"ukcharts09\">{{cite web |title=Chart For Week Up To 04/07/2009 |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/ |work=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=January 23, 2010 |df= }}</ref> The following week, the song reached its peak at number 12 on the UK Single Chart.<ref name=\"UK\" /> On July 12, 2009, \"Thriller\" peaked at number two on the [[Italian Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"italianchart09a\">{{cite web |url= http://italiancharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Thriller&cat=s |title= Thriller in Italian Chart |publisher= Hung Medien |accessdate= June 21, 2013}}</ref> and was later certified gold by the [[Federation of the Italian Music Industry]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.fimi.it/temp/cert_GFK_download_502011.pdf | publisher = [[Federation of the Italian Music Industry]] | language = Italian | accessdate = January 2, 2012 | title = Certificazioni Download FIMI | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120605021629/http://www.fimi.it/temp/cert_GFK_download_502011.pdf | archivedate = June 5, 2012 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> \"Thriller\" reached at number three on the Australian ARIA Chart and [[Swiss Singles Chart]] and topped the [[PROMUSICAE|Spanish Singles Charts]] for one week.<ref name=\"acharts\">{{cite web|url= http://acharts.us/song/7886 |title= Michael Jackson \u2013 Thriller \u2013 Music Charts |work= Acharts.us |publisher= aCharts.us |accessdate= January 23, 2010}}</ref> The song also placed within the top ten on the [[German Singles Chart]], Norwegian Singles Chart and [[Irish Singles Chart]], at number nine, number seven and number eight respectively.<ref name=\"acharts\" /> \"Thriller\" also landed at number 25 on the [[Danish Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"danishchart09\">{{cite web|title=Track Top 40 \u2013 July 10, 2009|url=http://www.hitlisterne.dk/tracklisten.asp?w=27&y=2009&list=t40|work=Hitlisterne.dk|publisher=IFPI Danmark & Nielsen Music Control.|accessdate=January 23, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930065038/http://www.hitlisterne.dk/tracklisten.asp?w=27&y=2009&list=t40|archivedate=September 30, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In the third week of July \"Thriller\" peaked at number 11 in Finland.<ref name=\"finnishchart2009a\"> {{cite web |url=http://finnishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Thriller&cat=s |title=Thriller in Finnish Chart |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=2010-01-23}}</ref> The song finished at #78 for the year on Billboard Hot 100 of 1984.\n\nIn 2013, \"Thriller\" re-entered the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at number 42.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/5785551/eminem-debuts-at-no-1-on-hot-rbhip-hop-songs-chart-michael|title=Eminem Debuts at No. 1 on Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs Chart; Michael Jackson's 'Thriller' Returns|publisher=|accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref> Also, in November 2018, it re-entered at number 31.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100|title=Top 100 Songs {{!}} Billboard Hot 100 Chart|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n{{Main article|Michael Jackson's Thriller (music video)}}\nThe [[music video]] for \"Thriller\" premiered on [[MTV]] on December 2, 1983.<ref name=\":3\" /> It was directed by [[John Landis]] and written by Landis and Jackson. In the video, Jackson and his girlfriend (played by [[Ola Ray]]) are confronted by zombies while walking home from a [[movie theater]]; Jackson becomes a [[zombie]] and performs a dance routine with a horde of the [[undead]]. The video references numerous [[Horror film|horror films]].<ref name=\"Griffin4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/features/2010/07/michael-jackson-thriller-201007?printable=true&currentPage=2|title=The \"Thriller\" Diaries|last=Griffin|first=Nancy|date=July 2010|work=Vanity Fair|accessdate=2011-01-02}}</ref>\n\nJackson contacted Landis after seeing his film ''[[An American Werewolf in London]].'' The pair conceived a 13-minute short film with a budget much larger than previous music videos. Jackson's record company refused to finance it, believing ''Thriller'' had peaked, so a making-of documentary, ''Making Michael Jackson's Thriller,'' was produced to receive financing from television networks.<ref name=\"Griffin\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/features/2010/07/michael-jackson-thriller-201007?printable=true&currentPage=2|title=The \"Thriller\" Diaries|last=Griffin|first=Nancy|date=July 2010|work=Vanity Fair|accessdate=2011-01-02}}</ref>\n\n''Michael Jackson's Thriller'' was launched to great anticipation and played regularly on [[MTV]]. It doubled sales of ''Thriller'', and sold over a million copies on [[VHS]], becoming the bestselling videotape at the time.<ref name=\"Griffin3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/features/2010/07/michael-jackson-thriller-201007?printable=true&currentPage=2|title=The \"Thriller\" Diaries|last=Griffin|first=Nancy|date=July 2010|work=Vanity Fair|accessdate=2011-01-02}}</ref> It is credited for transforming music videos into a serious art form, breaking down racial barriers in popular entertainment, and popularizing the making-of documentary format.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/nov/21/michael-jackson-thriller-changed-music-videos|title=How Michael Jackson's Thriller changed music videos for ever|last=Hebblethwaite|first=Phil|date=2013-11-21|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-10-29}}</ref>\n\nMany elements have had a lasting impact on popular culture, such as the zombie dance and [[Michael Jackson's Thriller jacket|Jackson's red jacket]], designed by Landis' wife [[Deborah Nadoolman Landis|Deborah Nadoolman]].<ref name=\":12\" /> Fans worldwide re-enact its zombie dance and it remains popular on [[YouTube]]. The [[Library of Congress]] described it as \"the most famous music video of all time\". In 2009, it became the first music video inducted into the [[National Film Registry]] as \"culturally, historically or aesthetically\" significant.<ref name=\"Griffin2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/features/2010/07/michael-jackson-thriller-201007?printable=true&currentPage=2|title=The \"Thriller\" Diaries|last=Griffin|first=Nancy|date=July 2010|work=Vanity Fair|accessdate=2011-01-02}}</ref>\n\n==Live performances==\n{{unreferenced section|date=March 2020}}\n\"Thriller\" was performed on all of Michael Jackson's solo tours and was slated to be performed during [[This Is It (concert residency)|This Is It]]. These concerts were unfortunately cancelled due to his death. \"Thriller\" was performed during [[Cirque Du Soleil]]'s [[Michael Jackson: The Immortal World Tour]] and is also featured on ''[[Immortal (Michael Jackson album)|Immortal]]''.\n\n== Cover versions ==\n<!-- Please put references into this article from reliable sources, or your edit may be deleted -->\n\n;1980s\n* In 1984, British comedian [[Lenny Henry]] recorded a spoof video of Thriller, titled \"Thinner\".\n* In 1989, American composer [[Henry Mancini]] and [[the Royal Philharmonic Orchestra]] recorded an orchestral version of the song.<ref name=\"coversproject.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.coversproject.com/artist/michael%20jackson/ |title=Michael Jackson Cover Songs |publisher=The Covers Project |accessdate=January 28, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927104513/http://www.coversproject.com/artist/michael%20jackson/ |archive-date=September 27, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n;2000s\n* In 2001, American-born Australian singer [[Joe Dolce]] covered the song on a compilation album, ''[[Andrew Denton's Musical Challenge]]''.<ref name=\"coversproject.com\" />\n* In 2003, British [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Aereogramme]] recorded \"Thriller\" for their ''[[Livers & Lungs EP]]''.<ref name=\"coversproject.com\" />\n* In 2004, British electronic music group [[the Prodigy]] sampled \"Thriller\" on their ''The Way It Is''.{{cn|date=September 2018}}\n* In 2007, [[Ian Brown]] covered \"Thriller\".<ref name=\"cover2\" /> Amos Barshad and Nick Catucci, of NYMag.com, commented that \"before you dismiss\" the song, if you \"give it a listen\", Brown\u2019s \"louche, drugged-out reinvention is actually pretty great.\"<ref name=\"cover2\">{{cite web |url=https://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2009/07/song_of_the_summer_takes_a_dee.html#ixzz0dUHkHtwO |title=Song of the Summer: Michael Jackson Rarities, Remixes, Covers and More! |author1=Amos Barshad |author2=Nick Catucci |work=NYMag.com |publisher=New York Media LLC |date=July 10, 2009 |accessdate=January 23, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/nme-video/youtube/id/KOVcSHgGHwc |title=Ian Brown \u2013 Thriller (Michael Jackson Cover) &#124; Video Youtube \u2013 NMETV Latest Music Videos and Clips |publisher=Nme.com |date=October 16, 2008 |accessdate=January 28, 2012}}</ref>\n* In 2008, German group [[Wise Guys (band)|Wise Guys]] recorded an a cappella version of the song as \"Schiller\" for their tenth album ''Frei!''. The stage choreography based on [[Michael Jackson's Thriller (music video)|Michael Jackson's music video]] and member Ferenc also recites a part of [[Friedrich Schiller]]'s ''[[Die B\u00fcrgschaft]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laut.de/Wise-Guys/Schiller |title='Schiller' von Wise Guys \u2013 laut.de \u2013 Song |publisher=Laut.de |date=November 16, 2011 |accessdate=January 28, 2012}}</ref>\n* In 2008, \"Thriller\" was also covered by [[Ben Gibbard]], lead singer of [[Death Cab for Cutie]] and [[the Postal Service]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicbyday.com/michael-jackson-thriller-covers/466/ |title=Michael Jackson Thriller Covers |author=Marvin Marks |work=MusicByDay.com |publisher=Music By Day |date=June 28, 2009 |accessdate=January 23, 2010}}</ref>\n* In 2008, industrial metal band [[Gothminister]] covered Jackson's song for their album ''[[Happiness in Darkness]]''.<ref name=\"coversproject.com\" />\n* In October 2009, [[Imogen Heap]] covered \"Thriller\" for [[BBC Radio|BBC Radio 1]] Live Lounge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spinner.com/2009/10/28/clash-of-the-cover-songs-michael-jackson-vs-imogen-heap/ |title=Clash of the Cover Songs: Michael Jackson vs. Imogen Heap |author=Ashley Lasimone |work=Spinner.com |publisher=[[American Online|AOL Inc]] |date=October 28, 2009 |accessdate=January 23, 2010}}</ref> \n;2010s\n* In 2010, [[Joey DeFrancesco]] recorded the song for his tribute album ''[[Never Can Say Goodbye: The Music of Michael Jackson]]''.\n* In 2011, [[Patrick Stump]] covered the song in an [[a cappella]] mash-up tribute along with several other Michael Jackson songs over pre-recorded backing vocals.<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/blogs/rolling-stone-video-blog/patrick-stump-pays-tribute-to-michael-jackson-in-awesome-a-cappella-medley-20110202 \"Patrick Stump Pays Tribute to Michael Jackson in Awesome A Cappella Medley\"]. Rolling Stone. Retrieved May 10, 2011.</ref>\n* In 2013, [[Jiordan Tolli]] covered an stripped-down slower version of song for [[The X Factor (Australia season 5)|fifth season]] of ''[[The X Factor (Australian TV series)|The X Factor Australia]]'' during week two. The cover was released as a single on September 3, 2013.{{cn|date=September 2018}} Tolli's performance of \"Thriller\" debuted at number 63 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/aria-singles-katy-perry-roar-spends-third-week-at-number-one-20130907|title=ARIA Singles: Katy Perry's Roar Spends Third Week at Number One|publisher=Noise11. Noise Network|date=September 7, 2013|accessdate=September 7, 2013}}</ref>\n* In 2014 and 2015, [[Demi Lovato]] covered the song on her [[Demi World Tour]]. This version included a remixed dancing at the end, which Lovato would dance to with background dancers.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/9811/20140908/watch-demi-lovato-cover-michael-jackson-thriller-world-tour-baltimore.htm|title=WATCH: Demi Lovato Covers Michael Jackson's 'Thriller' on DEMI World Tour Opening Night|journal=Music Times|date=September 8, 2014|accessdate=April 16, 2015}}</ref>\n*In 2017, [[Scandroid]] covered the song on the album ''Monochrome''.\n*In 2019, [[Ice Nine Kills]] covered the song on the album ''[[The Silver Scream]]: Final Cut''.<ref>https://www.rocksound.tv/news/read/ice-nine-kills-are-releasing-a-deluxe-version-of-their-album-the-silver-scr</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n* Written and composed by [[Rod Temperton]]\n* Produced by [[Quincy Jones]]\n* [[Michael Jackson]]: lead and background vocals, [[Linn LM-1|drum machine]]\n** Featuring: Narration by [[Vincent Price]] (Not featured on original edited single version)\n* Rod Temperton and Brian Banks: [[Roland Jupiter-8|synthesizers]]\n* [[Greg Phillinganes]]: synthesizers, [[Rhodes piano]], [[pipe organ]], [[Minimoog|Minimoog synth-bass]]\n* [[Anthony Marinelli]]: synthesizer programming\n* [[David Williams (guitarist)|David Williams]]: guitar\n{{Col-2}}\n* [[Jerry Hey]], Gary Grant: trumpets, [[flugelhorn]]s\n* [[Larry Williams (jazz musician)|Larry Williams]]: saxophone, flute\n* [[Bill Reichenbach Jr.|Bill Reichenbach]]: trombone\n* Vocal, rhythm and synthesizer arrangement by Rod Temperton\n* Horn arrangement by Jerry Hey\n* [[Sound effect|Effects]] by Bruce Cannon and Bruce Swedien\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Chart (1983\u201384)\n! Peak<br/>position\n|-\n| Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite book|last= Kent |first= David |title= Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992 |year= 2003 |isbn= 0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4\n|-\n| [[VRT Top 30|Belgian VRT Top 30]]<ref name=\"vrt\">{{cite web|url=http://top30-2.radio2.be/#/song-info/5161 |title=Michael Jackson \u2013 Thriller |work=[[VRT Top 30|Top30-3.radio2.be]] |publisher=VRT \u2013 Auguste Reyerslaan |language=Dutch |accessdate=January 24, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222214652/http://top30-2.radio2.be/ |archivedate=February 22, 2012 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1\n|-\n| Canadian [[RPM (magazine)|''RPM'' Top Singles]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.6705&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=kjerdnvbvl3a8p4jfufutrc7u6 |title= Top Singles \u2013 Volume 40, No. 1, March 10, 1984 |work= [[Canadian Singles Chart|RPM]] |accessdate= August 3, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20121017214623/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.6705&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=kjerdnvbvl3a8p4jfufutrc7u6 |archive-date= October 17, 2012 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3\n|-\n| France ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]])<ref name=\"frenchcharts1984\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1\n|-\n| Ireland ([[Irish Singles Chart|IRMA]])<ref name=\"IRL\">{{cite web |url=http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement |title= Search Results: Thriller |work=[[Irish Singles Chart|IrishCharts.ie]] |publisher= Irish Recorded Music Association |accessdate= January 25, 2010}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|3|artist=Michael Jackson|song=Thriller}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|6|artist=Michael Jackson|song=Thriller}}\n|-\n|Poland ([[Lista Przeboj\u00f3w Programu Trzeciego|LP3]])<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://lp3.polskieradio.pl/notowania/?numer=104|title=Top 30 Poland|magazine=[[Lista P